    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>u</m> is harmonic on the disk <m>B_R(x_0)</m>.
          Explain why no generality is lost in assuming the disk is centered at <m>0</m>
          when proving the mean value property on circles.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          Consider <m>v(x)=u(x + x_0)</m>.  
          Circles centered at <m>x_0</m> become circles centered at <m>0</m>.
        </p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>

  </section-->
  <page>

    <p>
      Assume <m>u</m> is harmonic in some open set <m>\Omega</m> with <m>B_r(0)\subseteq \Omega</m>.
    </p>

    <exercise><title>Defining <m>A(r)</m> and Showing it is Constant</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Define the circular average
        <md>
          A(r) = \frac{1}{2\pi} \int_0^{2\pi} u(r,\theta)\, d\theta.
        </md>

          Observe that this equals the arclength average

        <md>
          A(r) = \frac{1}{2\pi r}\int_{\partial B_r(0)} u\, ds.
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        Our goal is to show that, under the given hypotheses, <m>A(r)</m> is constant.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Observe, the polar Laplacian of <m>u</m> is given by
        </p>
        <md>
          \Delta u = u_{rr} + \frac{1}{r} u_r + \frac{1}{r^2} u_{\theta\theta}.
        </md>
        <p>
          Since <m>u</m> is harmonic, multiply by <m>r^2</m> to obtain:
        </p>
        <md>
          r^2 u_{rr} + r u_r + u_{\theta\theta} = 0.
        </md>
        <p>
          Use these facts (and integration) to prove that
        </p>
        
        <md>
          rA''(r) + A'(r) = 0.
        </md>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve this ODE. Show:
        </p>
        <md>
          (r A'(r))' = 0,
        </md>
        <p>
          hence
        </p>
        <md>
          rA'(r) = C.
        </md>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Argue that <m>C = 0</m> using boundedness of <m>A(r)</m> as <m>r \to 0^+</m>.
          Conclude <m>A'(r)=0</m> and <m>A(r)</m> is constant.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>
</page>
<page>

<exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>Show:</p>
        <md>
          \lim_{r\to 0^+} A(r) = u(0).
        </md>
        <p>
          Conclude the mean value property for a circle centered at the origin:
        </p>
        <md>
          u(0) = \frac{1}{2\pi}\int_0^{2\pi} u(r,\theta)\, d\theta.
        </md>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

      <exercise><title>Mean Value Property for Circles</title>
      
      
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>x_0 \in \Omega</m>. Using translation, show:
        </p>
        <md>
          u(x_0) = \frac{1}{2\pi r}\int_{\partial B_r(x_0)} u\, ds
        </md>
        <p>
          whenever <m>\overline{B_r(x_0)} \subset \Omega</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>


</page>
<page>
    <exercise>   <title>The Mean Value Property for Disks</title>
     <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>x_0\in\Omega</m>. Use the mean value property for circles to show that
        <md>
          u(x_0) = \frac{1}{\pi R^2}\int\int_{B_R(x_0)} u(r,\theta) dA.
        </md>
        Hint: Do a double integral in polar coordinates in the <m>d\theta dr</m> order. (we started using <m>R</m> because we need to integrate with respect to <m>r</m>.)
      </p>
     </statement> 


    </exercise>


